Please stay tuned for more information regarding Chromebook distribution, logins, etc. Thank you for your continued support and patience during these challenges.

Surline Middle School
August 18 at 5:44 PM ·

Congrats to STEM students Jaydon Botkins/Marissa Monroe and Lucas Hines/Nolan Illig for being chosen as finalists in the statewide Michigan Design Council contest for 2020! Students from all over the state were asked to design a product to help Michigan residents grow, transport, cook, serve or package healthy food sourced from within the state. As finalists in the competition, they will be provided a one on one mentoring session with a professional industrial designer to rapidly advance their design thinking and visual communication skills. Finalists will also be recognized for their design excellence in Michigan Design Council promotional media, award ceremonies, and through the MDC website.
Go Falcons!

KINDERGARTEN ROUND UP
Parent/Guardian of student entering kindergarten in the fall who was not already in GSRP (preschool):
Rose City School may pick up a kindergarten enrollment packet and complete it on May 11th and 12th from 9-3 during the scheduled packet pickup. If these days do not work, please contact Rose City School at 343-2248 to leave a message and we will contact you to schedule an appointment.
Surline Elementary is scheduling appointments by calling (989) 343-2189
Documentation required includes birth certificate, shot record and 2 proofs of residency.
Great Start Readiness Program (GSRP) registration information will be available next week.

DO NOT COME if you are symptomatic. Call or email us to discuss alternate options.

post_text: Rose City School Kindergarteners in Mrs. Baksa’s class had an amazing time acting as engineers and designing a structure! Their structure was a beanstalk, just like the beanstalk in the story, ‘Jack and the Beanstalk’. The goal of building the beanstalk was to make it as tall as possible while still capable of standing on its own. It was very challenging for the engineers to understand that failure can also be success. Mrs. Baksa found it extremely challenging, as the facilitator, to stand back and watch them struggle. Some students were very frustrated but, in the end, they are gaining a greater understanding of the design process. It was a wonderful exercise and experience for the students.

post_text: Rose City School 5th graders have been studying Native Americans and how they use their environment to meet their basic needs, such as food, clothing and shelter. The students first built structures in Minecraft (an application that allows players to build their own virtual worlds using blocks) before planning and building them in the Makerspace lab. Makerspace provide hands-on, creative ways to encourage students to design, experiment, build and invent as they deeply engage in science, engineering and tinkering. A makerspace is not solely a science lab, woodshop, computer lab or art room, but it may contain elements found in all of these familiar spaces.

post_text: Important information for parents of students a Surline Elementary! For more information go to Surline Elementary Facebook page or the building web page on the district web site.
shared_text:
Surline Elementary
August 19, 2019 at 1:00 PM ·

OK Parents, here we go!

If you have not already downloaded the PikMyKid App, please do so at this time. It will help us keep your child safer during dismissal times.

A PikMyKid Car Tag will be available for you at our Open House on Wednesday, August 21st . As you register in the App, use this number. You will be the Primary Parent for your child and in control of their dismissal. You can delegate alternate individuals, but they should have the App also as it will send a matching number to the phone for us to validate the correct person is picking up the proper child. If you are part of a car pool, each child’s number will be sent to the phone for validation. You will be asked for the necessary information (Child Name, Grade, Teacher, Dismissal Mode, & Car Tag Number) upon registration.

That’s All There Is To It!! We are on our way to a Safer School.

TIP #1 - Try Practicing with the App over the next couple days. We will notify you when we go live in approximately 5 days.

post_text: Still more “BEHIND THE SCENES” AT WBRC! A great deal happens ‘behind the scenes’ in the district that isn’t as obvious as more visible projects. Our Transportation Department Staff works all summer to prepare buses, plan routes, and make necessary repairs to keep all of our bus fleet rolling. These photos show our two mechanics doing body and engine repairs. Last year our bus fleet traveled approximately 433,000 miles transporting our students to and from school and to all of the extra-curricular activities.

post_text:
On June 12th, at the University of Michigan, the Michigan Design Council presented Surline Middle School 7th grader Dominik Smith with a gold level award for his industrial design concept. Dominik’s teacher, Mrs. Kathleen Palmer, was also presented with the Governor's Award for being Educator of the Year.
Over 600 students across Michigan entered their design entries and Dominik's was one of 12 who received an award! Every year that Mrs. Palmer's STEAM (Science, Technology, Engineering and Math) class has entered the contest they have gleaned awards. This is the 6th award Surline Middle School STEAM students have received in the three years that they have competed in the statewide competition.
This is a wonderful achievement for Dominik, for Mrs. Palmer and the STEAM program in our district. Congratulations all around; we look forward to more exciting things from this program!

post_text:
“Fourth graders at Surline Elementary had to write a persuasive court case regarding who showed the strongest character traits from the book ‘The Tiger Rising’. Students then had to present their case in front of their class.
Following this, the 4th grade students took a field trip to the 34th District Court to witness and participate in a real life mock court trial. Students got to participate in roles such as the prosecuting attorney, defense attorney, jurors, judge, bailiffs, and more! A really impactful learning experience!

post_text: After their Dairy Farm Unit in CBI, the class took a wonderful tour of Gallagher Dairy Farm. They learned about what takes place on a successful dairy farm. They were able to see each stage of a dairy farm from the very beginning with baby calves, to the milking parlor. They even got to go on a hayride and check out the pigs, kittens, and dogs. The Beck family graciously showed the students how a 4th generation family-run dairy farm is successfully done! The students have also been planting flowers and seeds they can use to plant in Mr. C’s (Ike Clelland’s) memory garden; it’s been a busy time of learning about farm and garden!

If you missed it this past September, please join us for a free showing of the Movie "RESILIENCE".
Monday, May 13th, from 6 – 7:30 p.m. at SES
CHILDCARE, free popcorn and door prizes, too!

Please see the attached flyer for details and how to register. The ‘click here’ URL is: https://tinyurl.com/y4ulhwfq [click on left pane below] or contact Darla Mckelvey at mckelveyd@michigan.gov

Researchers have discovered a dangerous biological syndrome caused by abuse and neglect during childhood. This documentary reveals that TOXIC STRESS can trigger hormones that wreak havoc on the brains and bodies of children, putting them at greater risk of disease, homelessness, prison time and early death. Resilience, however, also chronicles the dawn of a movement that is determined to FIGHT BACK. Please share!

post_text: Fourth grade students in Stephanie Dantzer's class at Rose City School are having to use their fraction math skills to unlock 'clues'! Students are using these skills to discover where the Forgetful Pharaoh left his Scepter in Ancient Egypt! They are required to reduce fractions to lowest terms, compare fractions, create equivalent fractions, add and subtract with LIKE denominators, and convert improper fractions to mixed number fractions to unlock clues. Then, using their powers of deduction, they narrow down the list of suspects to find the culprit and the cure!

post_text: OHHS ROV (Remote Operated Vehicle) Club members (Josh Anderson, Dylan Finkbeiner, Colin Finkbeiner, Colton Bragg, Derek Franciosi, CJ Gillette, Matthew Hughey and Brenden Erickson.) deserve congratulations on a job well done! On April 24th they worked without stopping from 9 am until 2 pm with over 2,000 elementary students from around the state of Michigan, explaining how ROVs are used in helping the environment and also how to control ROVs in the water. It was impressive to see how these boys handled the sheer number of students who came to their exhibit, patiently answering questions and teaching them how to work the controls. Many parents, teachers, and DEQ employees were overheard talking about our exhibit and how awesome our students were with their children. Our students represented OHHS very well and we are so proud of all of them. If you see them, please give them the kudos's they deserve, and many thanks to teachers Chris Powley and Dr. Carl Bragg.

post_text:
Mrs. Leibold’s CBI students at SMS and OHHS are always busy! The work at several local businesses. Pictured here, Mason is busy disinfecting the doors at Walgreens, Cheyenne is busy organizing the fabric at Caroline’s Sewing, and Ethan is busy straightening the book shelves at West Branch Public Library. They are all thoughtful, hard workers at their jobs!
After finishing their checking and savings accounts units in math, they visited Chemical Bank. Ms. Wilson, the Branch Manager, gave students a thorough and interesting tour of the bank and explained all the duties performed there. They learned about interest, loans and insurance, as well as checking and savings accounts. The students were thrilled to end their visit with special goody bags from Ms. Wilson and Chemical Bank!

M-STEP and SATs: It is the time of the year when our students have the opportunity to show their own superpowers and skills on state wide tests. DURING TESTING GOOD REST, GOOD NUTRITION, AND ATTENDING SCHOOL IS VERY IMPORTANT! The 8th grade will be testing on the mornings of Monday, April 8, PSAT testing Tuesday, April 9, and Monday, April 15. The 5th grade will be testing on the mornings of Wednesday, April 10, Thursday, April 11, Wednesday, April 17, and Thursday, April 18.
OHHS Juniors will be taking the SAT on Tuesday, April 9. OHHS Freshman, Sophomores and Juniors will be testing on Wednesday, April 10; Freshman and Sophomores taking the PSAT and Juniors the ACT Workkeys, . On Thursday, April 11, Juniors will be taking the M-STEP.
**Please encourage your child do put forth their best effort as they will be competing with all students in their grade level across the entire state of Michigan.**

post_text: State Representative Daire Rendon visited SMS to read to our 5th graders for March Reading Month. She shared a special story, The Pepperoni Palm Tree, which reinforced the importance of using our own talents and originality to be successful. She also shared her duties as our State Representative of Ogemaw County. Students were able to ask their own questions, too. Mrs. Rendon personally invited us to visit her at the State Capital on April 12 when the 5th grade class goes on a field trip there.

post_text: Staff from Michigan State University Extension, including Peggy Zettle, Dorothy Munn and Bev Przystas, presented to high school seniors about money management on Wednesday, April 3rd, in the OHHS auditorium. They shared a couple of great modules with the seniors including ‘Money Management: Control Your Cash Flow’ and ‘Borrowing: Use – Don’t Abuse’. Great information for these seniors as they prepare to go to secondary education or the workforce or wherever life leads them. Thanks to Principal Doan for arranging this and to MSUE staff members for sharing their time, expertise and resources!

SAVE THE DATE! Thursday, April 11th, the WBRC Bands, Choirs, and OHHS Art department are hosting a ‘Fine Arts Extravaganza’ at 6pm in the OHHS Auditorium. The event is designed to give a snapshot of our 7-12 Music Programs and our 9-12 Visual Arts.

In addition to the performances and art displays, there will be a silent auction benefiting the WBRC Music Boosters and Ms. Dowd will have some art available for purchase to benefit the OHHS Art Department.

Thank you all for your continued support of all of our WBRC Arts Programs; we hope to see you there!

THE LAST DAY OF SCHOOL has been REVISED due to the 12 snow days we had this year. Each year the state forgives the first six snow days. We were granted an additional three days of forgiveness by the State Superintendent, leaving a balance of three days to be made up at the end of this school year.

The last day is Tuesday, June 18 *, for students, and this is a half day.

A revised calendar is on our website.
[The last day for support and certified is to be determined].

* Please note this is subject to change if we have additional inclement weather that causes school to be canceled.

post_text: The Board of Education had the pleasure of meeting and hearing about each of the Top Ten academically achieving seniors from OHHS at their regular meeting on Monday, March 18th. Principal Doan introduced each student and shared their achievements and future plans as their proud parents stood, and then the student presented their parent(s) with a rose. Congratulations to the following students: (10) Kyle Winter, (9) Trevor Likavec, (8) Olivia Getzinger (7) Dylan Finkbeiner, (6) Nicholas Marentette, (5) Kaitlin Randall, (4) Margaret Kearns, (3) Colton Bragg, (2) Salutatorian Reese Temple and (1) Valedictorian Colin Finkbeiner. [Pictures courtesy of Jan Wackerle]
